{# FAQ #}
<section class="py-12">
  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4">
    <h2 class="section-heading mb-8">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <div class="space-y-4">
      <details class="card p-5 group" open>
        <summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white">
          What visa do I need to work in Germany as a tech professional?
          <i data-lucide="chevron-down" class="w-5 h-5 text-gray-400 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform"></i>
        </summary>
        <p class="mt-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 text-sm leading-relaxed">
          The most common pathway is the <strong>EU Blue Card</strong>, designed for highly skilled workers. You need a recognized university degree and a job offer with a minimum salary (around €45,300 for shortage occupations like IT). Germany also offers a standard work visa and the new Chancenkarte (opportunity card) for job seekers. All employers listed here provide visa sponsorship.
        </p>
      </details>
      <details class="card p-5 group">
        <summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white">
          Do I need to speak German to work in tech in Germany?
          <i data-lucide="chevron-down" class="w-5 h-5 text-gray-400 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform"></i>
        </summary>
        <p class="mt-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 text-sm leading-relaxed">
          Most tech companies in Berlin, Munich, and other major cities use English as their working language. You can work successfully in English, especially at international companies and startups. However, learning German is highly recommended for daily life, bureaucracy, and long-term career growth.
        </p>
      </details>
      <details class="card p-5 group">
        <summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white">
          What is the average tech salary in Germany?
          <i data-lucide="chevron-down" class="w-5 h-5 text-gray-400 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform"></i>
        </summary>
        <p class="mt-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 text-sm leading-relaxed">
          Tech salaries in Germany typically range from €55,000–€75,000 for mid-level engineers, €75,000–€100,000+ for seniors, and €100,000–€130,000+ for staff/principal engineers. Munich tends to pay higher than Berlin, but also has a higher cost of living. Use our <a href="/tools/salary-calculator/" class="text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-400 hover:underline">Salary Calculator</a> for detailed comparisons.
        </p>
      </details>
      <details class="card p-5 group">
        <summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white">
          How long does it take to get a work visa for Germany?
          <i data-lucide="chevron-down" class="w-5 h-5 text-gray-400 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform"></i>
        </summary>
        <p class="mt-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 text-sm leading-relaxed">
          Processing times vary by country and embassy. Typically, an EU Blue Card application takes 4–8 weeks after submitting your documents at the German embassy. Your employer's relocation team usually handles the paperwork. Once in Germany, you'll need to register your address and visit the Foreigners' Office (Ausländerbehörde) to finalize your residence permit.
        </p>
      </details>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

